<span id="freeTextContainer11363578371233387093">Wow. I’m struggling to find words. The fact that the author knew and had a friendship with one of our countries most violent serial killers makes this such a haunting read. I appreciate how candid she was about her thoughts on Ted and the whole journey. I learned a lot about what he actually did. I kind of knew things...but I learned a lot. And a lot of it made me sick to my stomach. There was a point where I wanted to time travel (back to before I was born) and slap one of his lawyers across th</span>
  <span id="freeText11363578371233387093" style="display:none">Wow. I’m struggling to find words. The fact that the author knew and had a friendship with one of our countries most violent serial killers makes this such a haunting read. I appreciate how candid she was about her thoughts on Ted and the whole journey. I learned a lot about what he actually did. I kind of knew things...but I learned a lot. And a lot of it made me sick to my stomach. There was a point where I wanted to time travel (back to before I was born) and slap one of his lawyers across the face. She was a woman and the things she said in his defense...I can’t even comprehend them. And of course there are things we will never know. This is one of the best nonfiction books I’ve read. It was fascinating and hard to read and I couldn’t put it down. Amazing.</span>
