    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1252764379" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1252764379" />
    <a title="Kavita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita"><img alt="Kavita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1315387023p2/5858699.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1252764379?book_show_action=true">Apr 12, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kavita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kavita" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita">Kavita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=true-crime">true-crime</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=usa">usa</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1252764379" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13890784605813029909"><i>
  <b>We serial killers are your sons, we are your husbands, we are everywhere. And there will be more of your children dead tomorrow.</b>
</i><br/><br/>What are the chances of a ex-policewoman turned journalist working on a story about random murders taking place in the country actually having worked at close quarters with the same serial killer in a crisis centre? That&apos;s a pretty unique position to be in and Ann Rule was unfortunate enough to be on the spot. She had bonded with Ted over months of saving people&apos;s l</span>
  <span id="freeText13890784605813029909" style="display:none"><i>
  <b>We serial killers are your sons, we are your husbands, we are everywhere. And there will be more of your children dead tomorrow.</b>
</i><br /><br />What are the chances of a ex-policewoman turned journalist working on a story about random murders taking place in the country actually having worked at close quarters with the same serial killer in a crisis centre? That's a pretty unique position to be in and Ann Rule was unfortunate enough to be on the spot. She had bonded with Ted over months of saving people's lives together and never in her wildest dreams did she realise that the same Ted was also murdering young women all over the place at the same time that he was saving people from committing suicide.<br /><br />This is a fascinating and frightening book that focuses on how psychopaths are in our midst and we don't recognise them. Rule struggles to accept the truth as gradually one by one, the evidence piles up against Bundy. Vacillating from fear to tenderness, from friendship to hate, from a desire to get Bundy receive the help he badly needed to a need to tell the victim's stories, Rule has written a comprehensive and insightful book about this case. Her emotions come through in the book and for this, I can forgive the average writing and the author getting in the way of the narrative at times.<br /><br />The book starts off with several clarifications and a FAQ for people who keep writing to Rule asking the same things over and over again. The actual 'story' starts with Ted's escape from prison and then moves back and forth. The author follows the different murders and disappearances one by one and keeps the knowledge of the culprit or the end result from the reader for the first half of the book. It is almost like you are following the case for several years in exactly the same way as the investigators did. The descriptions of the trials take up a good chunk of the latter half of the book. While I generally find this section pretty boring in most true crime books, it was not the case with this one. I don't know whether it was the skill of the author in involving me so deep into the events of the time, or Bundy's <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GkjfyERs5Jc" rel="nofollow noopener">shenanigans in court</a>. But I was interested till the end. Rule and Bundy corresponded over a long period, and she shared some of his letters in the book, which I found rather enlightening.<br /><br />The author might have been friends with a serial killer but she also shows respect and sympathy for the murdered women and their families. Almost every woman was given a short biography, and the subject was dealt with very delicately. Rule makes the point again and again that these women did nothing wrong, and there was simply no way they could have escaped, except by a stroke of luck. It is indeed true. There was no way anyone could have suspected Ted Bundy to be a murderer, with his good looks and charm. Rule also retains enough sympathy for Bundy and wonders what could have been done to prevent his turning into a monster. A man with so much promise, knowledge and intellect ending up as a common criminal is a waste of not just his life, but that of all the smart and intelligent women he murdered. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Bundy put the blame for his murder spree on <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vlk_sRU49TI" rel="nofollow noopener">pornography</a>. It is anyone's guess if this is the case, but I personally think that if pornography had an effect on Bundy, it was only to enhance what had already been created inside him. I certainly don't believe the monster was created because of a rejection by a woman. I personally think that his <a href="http://articles.philly.com/1989-01-25/news/26122339_1_bundy-louise-cowell-violent-childhood" rel="nofollow noopener">maternal grandfather, Samuel Cowell, abuser and bigot extraordinnaire</a>, abused Bundy when he was a child. The very fact that Bundy talks of this horrible man as loving and wonderful is a red flag since no one else thinks so! Rule appears to agree with me. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />We get to see Bundy through the eyes of a person who had known him under ordinary circumstances as an ordinary person. And that is why this book is so creepy and disturbing. A seemingly ordinary man with oodles of charm goes about murdering women without anyone realising it at all! It shows how vulnerable we really are in the face of a maniacal and intelligent killer. And now I am off to double-check that the doors and windows are locked ...</span>
  <a data-text-id="13890784605813029909" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

